    "Then one has a unique splitting of the form (3) on S +, and it is the splitting induced by that on the singular sector containing the midpoint of S or, if the midpoint is a singular direction, the singular sector starting there.",
    "This splitting is called the canonical splitting on S +.",
    "A similar statement obviously holds for S -.",
    "We are now in the position to reinterpret the notion of deformation data from [Moc25] in the language of canonical splittings introduced above.",
